## Open-source projects to build on, not reinvent

Three GitHub repositories form the foundation you should build on top of:

| Project | Stars | Purpose | Key strength |
|---------|-------|---------|-------------|
| **jldbc/pybaseball** | 1,600 | Baseball data retrieval | One-liner access to FanGraphs, Statcast, BBRef |
| **uberfastman/yfpy** | 247 | Yahoo Fantasy API wrapper | Most comprehensive Yahoo integration |
| **DimaKudosh/pydfs-lineup-optimizer** | 441 | DFS lineup optimization | PuLP-based ILP solver with MLB support |

Beyond these three, the landscape thins considerably. **No well-maintained open-source trade analyzer exists** for season-long Yahoo fantasy baseball — this is the biggest gap you'd need to fill with custom code. The **baseballforecaster** project (baileymorton989) uses Monte Carlo simulations for player projections and Monte Carlo Search Trees for draft simulation, offering interesting methodology to study. The **Fantasy-Baseball-App** by parkergeis demonstrates a working Streamlit dashboard for ESPN leagues with weekly scoreboards and player percentile visualizations.

An emerging category worth watching: **MCP (Model Context Protocol) servers for baseball data**. Projects like `etweisberg/mlb-mcp` and `alex-rimerman/statcast-mcp` enable AI assistants to query Statcast and FanGraphs data via natural language — a pattern that could integrate directly with Claude for on-demand analysis.

The **Smart Fantasy Baseball Player ID Map** is an essential utility — it bridges player IDs across Yahoo, ESPN, FanGraphs, MLBAM, Baseball Reference, Fantrax, and DraftKings. Without this crosswalk, merging league data from Yahoo with projection data from FanGraphs is a painful manual process.

